271:  Direct from \lstinline{CategoryTheory.Abelian.Ext.linearEquiv₀} applied to the abelian category $\Sheaf(J, \ModuleCat\,k)$, which is $\Linear k$-enriched (auto-inferable from the prerequisites of Section~\ref{sec:moduleK_prereqs}) and has $\HasExt$ (Theorem~\ref{thm:HasExt_Sheaf_Opens_ModuleCatK}). The $\noncomputable$ \lstinline{abbrev} reducibility of $\HModule\,k\,F\,0$ (Definition~\ref{def:Scheme_HModule}) lets instance synthesis unfold the wrapper to the underlying $\Ext$ group, and \lstinline{linearEquiv₀} returns the $\Module k$-linear bijection between that $\Ext$ group and the corresponding Hom group in the sheaf category. The closure body is therefore a one-liner \lstinline{Abelian.Ext.linearEquiv₀}; iter-010 plan-agent \lstinline{lean_run_code} probe confirms the closure compiles end-to-end against current Mathlib.
275:  Mathlib provides three flavours of the $\Ext^0 \simeq \Hom$ equivalence: \lstinline{Abelian.Ext.homEquiv₀} (plain $\simeq$), \lstinline{Abelian.Ext.addEquiv₀} (additive $\simeq^+$), \lstinline{Abelian.Ext.linearEquiv₀} ($R$-linear $\simeq_R$). The iter-010 implementation chooses the strongest, \lstinline{linearEquiv₀}, because the $k$-linear refinement is the one consumed downstream: $\Module.\mathtt{Finite}\,k\,(\HModule\,k\,F\,0) \iff \Module.\mathtt{Finite}\,k\,((\mathtt{constantSheaf}\dots) \to F)$ via \lstinline{Module.Finite.equiv}, which requires a $\Module k$-linear equivalence on its left side.
278:\begin{remark}[Why this bridge and not \texttt{HModule\_forget}]
279:  Session~15's \texttt{recommendations.md} proposed an alternative iter-010 polish lemma \lstinline{HModule_forget}: a simp lemma identifying the $\forget_2 (\ModuleCat\,k)\,\AddCommGrpCat$-image of $\HModule\,k\,F\,n$ with $\Sheaf.\mathtt H\,((\sheafCompose\,\_\,(\forget_2\,\dots)).\mathrm{obj}\,F)\,n$. Iter-010 plan-agent re-read of Mathlib's \lstinline{CategoryTheory/Sites/SheafCohomology/Basic.lean} reveals that $\Sheaf.\mathtt H\,F\,n := \Ext\bigl((\mathtt{constantSheaf}\,J\,\_).\mathrm{obj}\,(\AddCommGrpCat.\mathrm{of}\,(\ULift\,\mathbb Z)),\ F,\ n\bigr)$ — the unit object is $\ULift\,\mathbb Z$, whereas $\HModule$ uses $\ModuleCat.\mathrm{of}\,k\,k$. The two unit objects are unrelated under $\forget_2 (\ModuleCat\,k)\,\AddCommGrpCat$ (the former forgets to $\AddCommGrpCat.\mathrm{of}\,k$, not $\AddCommGrpCat.\mathrm{of}\,(\ULift\,\mathbb Z)$). The two cohomology theories are related by a change-of-coefficient comparison map, but it is generically not an isomorphism — so \lstinline{HModule_forget} as proposed is not a \lstinline{rfl}/single-application closure. Iter-010 instead targets this $H^0$ bridge, which is genuinely a one-liner and is the algebraic fact downstream consumers actually need.
284:The composition of the four typeclass instances of Sections~\ref{sec:moduleK_prereqs}–\ref{sec:moduleK_ext}, Definition~\ref{def:Scheme_toModuleKSheaf}, and Definition~\ref{def:Scheme_HModule} delivers Phase~A step~5 in full and bridges to Phase~A step~6:
289:      H^n_{\Module\,k}(C, \struct C) \;:=\; \mathtt{HModule}\,k\,(\toModuleKSheaf\,C)\,n
291:    is well-defined and automatically carries a $\Module\,k$ instance, so $\Module.\mathtt{finrank}\,k\,(\HModule\,k\,(\toModuleKSheaf\,C)\,1) : \mathbb N$ is well-defined.
292:  \item The forgetful functor $\ModuleCat\,k \to \AddCommGrpCat$ recovers the iter-004 abelian-group cohomology (Definition~\ref{def:Scheme_toModuleKSheaf_forgetCompare}), so the new $\HModule$ commutes with the existing $\Sheaf.\mathtt H$ on the underlying type level.
293:  \item Phase~A step~6 (Serre finiteness, $\finrank_k H^i(C, \mathcal F) < \infty$) remains the deep work to come, but is now expressible inside Mathlib's standard $\Module\,k$ API: the statement of Serre finiteness becomes a $\Module.\mathtt{Finite}\,k\,(\HModule\,k\,F\,n)$ predicate.
